BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260314T093000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260314T103000
LOCATION:Lewis &amp\; Clark Graduate School\, South Chapel
SUMMARY:An Intercultural Approach to Clinical Supervision to Support Mult
 icultural Effectiveness (In-Person)
DESCRIPTION:Intercultural communication can complement and deepen traditi
 onal diversity frameworks such as social justice\, multicultural counseli
 ng\, and liberation psychology. It can also help ground our work as clini
 cal supervisors\, and pinpoint more specific ways to support our supervis
 ees.  This workshop explores the use of a developmental intercultural app
 roach to effectively navigate diversity\, social justice\, and multicultu
 ral counseling challenges in clinical supervision.&#160\;  While this wor
 kshop may not result in the easy answers we sometimes crave when it comes
  to these challenges\, it will offer some specific concepts\, models\, an
 d considerations when it comes to being mentors in these areas.Following 
 this workshop\, participants will have the ability to:      Describe thre
 e key positions from the Developmental Model of Intercultural Sensitivity
  (DMIS) and how they relate to supervisee development\, in relationship t
 o intercultural effectiveness          Discuss the likely flaw related to
  universalism when it comes to culture          Relate the DMIS to two fo
 rms of racism          Identify one common training dilemma related to cu
 ltural competency goals          Discuss the benefits of the culture shar
 e activity with your supervisee          Discuss the main point of a supe
 rvision interaction framework and how it may impact the supervision relat
 ionship          Name potential consequences of using shame as a strategy
  for learning and change when it comes to the development of intercultura
 l effectiveness          Explain how at least two cultural dimensions cou
 ld impact the feedback process in supervision    State at least one way t
 o support a shift from one position to the next for each of the three key
  positions    This workshop may meet the OBLPCT Cultural Competence Conti
 nuing Education requirement. Click here for more information (http://www.
 oregon.gov/oblpct/Pages/CCCE.aspx)Details &amp\; RegistrationRegistration
  for this workshop is closedDate and Time: Saturday\, March 14\, 2026\, 9
 :30 a.m.-4:30 p.m.Location: Lewis &amp\; Clark Graduate School\, South Ch
 apelInstructor: Cheryl Forster\, PsyDCost and Credits: $165\, includes 5.
 5 CEUs. GSEC Alumni\, Adjuncts\, and Clinical Mental Health Supervisors s
 ave 20%.  About the Instructor  As a psychologist and an Asian-American w
 oman\, Dr. Cheryl Forster brings a strong and unique set of skills to her
  work as an intercultural trainer. Dr. Forster's continuing education and
  organizational workshops focus on incorporating and integrating the inte
 rcultural approach to diversity\, which is complementary to and can enhan
 ce more traditional perspectives like social justice\, liberation psychol
 ogy\, diversity\, equity\, and inclusion.  Some of her postgraduate study
  highlights include an Intercultural Practitioner Certificate from the hi
 ghly respected Intercultural Communication Institute\, completing the Bra
 in\, Mind &amp\; Culture Masterclass Certification from the Japan Intercu
 ltural Institute\, being a Qualified Administrator of the Intercultural D
 evelopment Inventory\, earning an Intercultural Development Diploma from 
 the Intercultural Development Research Institute\, and becoming a Certifi
 ed CQ Facilitator (all-in-all\, she has completed over 800 hours of train
 ing in intercultural communication with many of the leaders in the field)
 . She has also completed specialized training in trauma\, EMDR\, interper
 sonal neurobiology\, attachment\, Polyvagal Theory\, integrative somatic 
 trauma therapy\, embodied activism\, and ambiguous loss.  Since 2005\, sh
 e has worked at Portland State University's (PSU) Center for Student Heal
 th and Counseling\; currently as the Lead Coordinator of Training and Int
 ercultural Specialist. She is a former Association of Counseling Center T
 raining Agencies' (ACCTA) Diversity Scholar and served on the ACCTA Board
  of Directors from 2017 to 2019. She taught a class at the Middlebury Ins
 titute of International Studies at Monterey in 2018 and is a contributing
  author in The SAGE Encyclopedia of Intercultural Competence (2015). More
  recently\, she taught a class on working with adult BIPOC adoptees for P
 SU's Counselor Education department. In 2012\, her commitment to the lear
 ning process led her to establish her professional intercultural training
  business Bookmark Connections (https://bookmarkconnections.com/).New wor
 kshops and trainings are added to our calendar regularly. For the latest 
 on professional development related to your specific interests\, sign up 
 for our mailing list! (https://lclark.tfaforms.net/4735441)
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  Intercultura
 l communication can complement and deepen traditional diversity framework
 s such as social justice\, multicultural counseling\, and liberation psyc
 hology. It can also help ground our work as clinical supervisors\, and pi
 npoint more specific ways to support our supervisees.</p><p style="line-h
 eight: 1.5\;">  This workshop explores the use of a developmental intercu
 ltural approach to effectively navigate diversity\, social justice\, and 
 multicultural counseling challenges in clinical supervision.&#160\;</p><p
  style="line-height: 1.5\;">  While this workshop may not result in the e
 asy answers we sometimes crave when it comes to these challenges\, it wil
 l offer some specific concepts\, models\, and considerations when it come
 s to being mentors in these areas.</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;"><stro
 ng>Following this workshop\, participants will have the ability to:</stro
 ng></p><ul><li><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">      Describe three key pos
 itions from the Developmental Model of Intercultural Sensitivity (DMIS) a
 nd how they relate to supervisee development\, in relationship to intercu
 ltural effectiveness    </p></li><li><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">      
 Discuss the likely flaw related to universalism when it comes to culture 
    </p></li><li><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">      Relate the DMIS to tw
 o forms of racism    </p></li><li><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">      Ide
 ntify one common training dilemma related to cultural competency goals   
  </p></li><li><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">      Discuss the benefits of
  the culture share activity with your supervisee    </p></li><li><p style
 ="line-height: 1.5\;">      Discuss the main point of a supervision inter
 action framework and how it may impact the supervision relationship    </
 p></li><li><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">      Name potential consequence
 s of using shame as a strategy for learning and change when it comes to t
 he development of intercultural effectiveness    </p></li><li><p style="l
 ine-height: 1.5\;">      Explain how at least two cultural dimensions cou
 ld impact the feedback process in supervision    </p></li><li>State at le
 ast one way to support a shift from one position to the next for each of 
 the three key positions  </li></ul><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  This w
 orkshop may meet the <strong>OBLPCT Cultural Competence Continuing Educat
 ion</strong> requirement. <a href="http://www.oregon.gov/oblpct/Pages/CCC
 E.aspx">Click here for more information</a></p><hr /><h2><strong>Details 
 &amp\; Registration</strong></h2><h5 style="line-height: 1.5\;"><strong>R
 egistration for this workshop is closed</strong></h5><p style="line-heigh
 t: 1.5\;"><strong>Date and Time:</strong> Saturday\, March 14\, 2026\, 9:
 30 a.m.-4:30 p.m.</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;"><strong>Location:</str
 ong> Lewis &amp\; Clark Graduate School\, South Chapel</p><p><strong>Inst
 ructor:</strong> Cheryl Forster\, PsyD</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;"><
 strong>Cost and Credits:</strong> $165\, includes 5.5 CEUs. GSEC Alumni\,
  Adjuncts\, and Clinical Mental Health Supervisors save 20%.</p><hr /><h2
 >  About the Instructor</h2><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  As a psycholo
 gist and an Asian-American woman\, Dr. Cheryl Forster brings a strong and
  unique set of skills to her work as an intercultural trainer. Dr. Forste
 r's continuing education and organizational workshops focus on incorporat
 ing and integrating the intercultural approach to diversity\, which is co
 mplementary to and can enhance more traditional perspectives like social 
 justice\, liberation psychology\, diversity\, equity\, and inclusion.</p>
 <p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  Some of her postgraduate study highlights
  include an Intercultural Practitioner Certificate from the highly respec
 ted Intercultural Communication Institute\, completing the Brain\, Mind &
 amp\; Culture Masterclass Certification from the Japan Intercultural Inst
 itute\, being a Qualified Administrator of the Intercultural Development 
 Inventory\, earning an Intercultural Development Diploma from the Intercu
 ltural Development Research Institute\, and becoming a Certified CQ Facil
 itator (all-in-all\, she has completed over 800 hours of training in inte
 rcultural communication with many of the leaders in the field). She has a
 lso completed specialized training in trauma\, EMDR\, interpersonal neuro
 biology\, attachment\, Polyvagal Theory\, integrative somatic trauma ther
 apy\, embodied activism\, and ambiguous loss.</p><p style="line-height: 1
 .5\;">  Since 2005\, she has worked at Portland State University's (PSU) 
 Center for Student Health and Counseling\; currently as the Lead Coordina
 tor of Training and Intercultural Specialist. She is a former Association
  of Counseling Center Training Agencies' (ACCTA) Diversity Scholar and se
 rved on the ACCTA Board of Directors from 2017 to 2019. She taught a clas
 s at the Middlebury Institute of International Studies at Monterey in 201
 8 and is a contributing author in The SAGE Encyclopedia of Intercultural 
 Competence (2015). More recently\, she taught a class on working with adu
 lt BIPOC adoptees for PSU's Counselor Education department. In 2012\, her
  commitment to the learning process led her to establish her professional
  intercultural training business <a href="https://bookmarkconnections.com
 /">Bookmark Connections</a><span style="background-color: transparent\;">
 .</span></p><div id="lw_widget_470b39ba" class="lw_widget lw_widget_type_
 blurbs lw_widget_blurbs lw_widget_id_3994 lw_widget_opt_in lw_widget_pagi
 nation"><ul class="lw_widget_results lw_widget_results_blurbs"><li class=
 "lw_item_1"><div class="lw_blurbs_body"><p style="line-height: 1.5\;"><em
 ><strong>New workshops and trainings are added to our calendar regularly.
 </strong> For the latest on professional development related to your spec
 ific interests\, <a href="https://lclark.tfaforms.net/4735441">sign up fo
 r our mailing list!</a></em></p></div></li></ul></div>
