BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260404T110000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260404T153000
LOCATION:Online
SUMMARY:Working with Sex and Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder (Online)
DESCRIPTION:This two-part workshop explores the complex and commonly over
 looked intersection of sexuality and Obsessive Compulsive Disorder (OCD).
 Topics discussed will include:Common sexual subthemes and their symptoms 
  Sociocultural influences of sexual subthemes  OCD's interference with se
 x and relationships  Navigating the clinical pitfalls to working with sex
  and OCD  Community resources for OCD clients and their loved ones    Inf
 ormation will be presented from a multidimensional approach\, reviewing t
 he implications of societal erotophobia (sex negativity) on both client a
 nd clinician perspectives.&#160\;Following this workshop\, participants w
 ill have an increased understanding of:      OCD and related terms/concep
 ts (obsessions\, compulsions\, intrusive thoughts\, exposure exercises\, 
 etc.)          How OCD clients may be specifically impacted by ableism\, 
 public misunderstanding\, and how healthcare provider misunderstanding of
  OCD leads to further stigma\, shame\, misdiagnosis\, and barriers to tre
 atment          How sociocultural context impacts sexual subthemes and cl
 ient sexuality          How to properly assess\, diagnose and refer OCD c
 lients to appropriate treatment          At least three myths that misrep
 resent sexuality and OCD\, and how to debunk them          How to navigat
 e countertransference that clinicians commonly experience with sexuality 
 and OCD.          At least three ways to support OCD clients in a therapy
  setting\, regarding sexual themes and/or sexuality.    Please note: This
  workshop may include case stories\, video\, language\, texts or other ma
 terial that address topics of suicidality\, violence\, sexual assault\, a
 nd violence against children. Read more (https://www.lclark.edu/programs/
 continuing_education/about/#emotionalcontent) of our emotional content st
 atementDetails &amp\; RegistrationDate and Time: Saturdays\, April 4 &amp
 \; 11\, 2026\, 11 a.m.-3:30 p.m. PST\, OnlineInstructor: Renee Fitzpatric
 k\, LMHC\, LPC\, CSTCost and Credits: $160\, includes 8 CEUs. Alumni\, Ad
 juncts\, and GSEC Clinical Supervisors save 20%. $75 GSEC student rate.&#
 160\;Register Online (https://lclark.tfaforms.net/wf1W4MQ?epid=a1aUY00000
 26GiT)Registration ends after Wednesday\, April 1stAccessibility: We are 
 committed to making our events accessible to all needs and abilities. Whe
 n registering\, please let us know your access needs. Contact us at 503-7
 68-6040 or cce@lclark.edu (mailto:cce@lclark.edu)&#160\;with questions.Pl
 ease note: Discounted &#x2018\;Student Rate&#x2019\; registrations are fo
 r current students only and do not include continuing education credit (C
 EU/PDUs)  About the InstructorRenee Fitzpatrick\, LMHC\, LPC\, CST (she/h
 er) is a Licensed Professional Counselor and AASECT-certified Sex Therapi
 st currently working with individuals\, families and relationship-systems
  with her private practice with OR and WA-based clients. Renee is also an
  adjunct professor for the CMHC\, CTSP and MCFT programs within Lewis &am
 p\; Clark's Graduate School for Counseling Education. Renee specializes i
 n working with sexually-marginalized communities\, including disabled and
  neurodivergent clients. Renee is a clinician with lived experience havin
 g OCD who provides Exposure &amp\; Response Prevention Treatment (ERP) fo
 r clients suffering with OCD.New workshops and trainings are added to our
  calendar regularly. For the latest on professional development related t
 o your specific interests\, sign up for our mailing list! (https://lclark
 .tfaforms.net/4735441)
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  This two-par
 t workshop explores the complex and commonly overlooked intersection of s
 exuality and Obsessive Compulsive Disorder (OCD).</p><p style="line-heigh
 t: 1.5\;"><strong>Topics discussed will include:</strong></p><ul><li styl
 e="line-height: 1.5\;">Common sexual subthemes and their symptoms  </li><
 li style="line-height: 1.5\;">Sociocultural influences of sexual subtheme
 s  </li><li style="line-height: 1.5\;">OCD's interference with sex and re
 lationships  </li><li style="line-height: 1.5\;">Navigating the clinical 
 pitfalls to working with sex and OCD  </li><li style="line-height: 1.5\;"
 >Community resources for OCD clients and their loved ones  </li></ul><p s
 tyle="line-height: 1.5\;">  Information will be presented from a multidim
 ensional approach\, reviewing the implications of societal erotophobia (s
 ex negativity) on both client and clinician perspectives.&#160\;</p><p st
 yle="line-height: 1.5\;"><strong>Following this workshop\, participants w
 ill have an increased understanding of:</strong></p><ul><li><p style="lin
 e-height: 1.5\;">      OCD and related terms/concepts (obsessions\, compu
 lsions\, intrusive thoughts\, exposure exercises\, etc.)    </p></li><li>
 <p style="line-height: 1.5\;">      How OCD clients may be specifically i
 mpacted by ableism\, public misunderstanding\, and how healthcare provide
 r misunderstanding of OCD leads to further stigma\, shame\, misdiagnosis\
 , and barriers to treatment    </p></li><li><p style="line-height: 1.5\;"
 >      How sociocultural context impacts sexual subthemes and client sexu
 ality    </p></li><li><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">      How to properly
  assess\, diagnose and refer OCD clients to appropriate treatment    </p>
 </li><li><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">      At least three myths that mi
 srepresent sexuality and OCD\, and how to debunk them    </p></li><li><p 
 style="line-height: 1.5\;">      How to navigate countertransference that
  clinicians commonly experience with sexuality and OCD.    </p></li><li><
 p style="line-height: 1.5\;">      At least three ways to support OCD cli
 ents in a therapy setting\, regarding sexual themes and/or sexuality.    
 </p></li></ul><p class="p1" style="font-size: 14px\; line-height: 1.5\;">
 <strong>Please note:</strong> This workshop may include case stories\, vi
 deo\, language\, texts or other material that address topics of suicidali
 ty\, violence\, sexual assault\, and violence against children. <a href="
 https://www.lclark.edu/programs/continuing_education/about/#emotionalcont
 ent" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Read more</a> of our emotional conten
 t statement</p><hr /><h2><strong>Details &amp\; Registration</strong></h2
 ><p style="line-height: 1.5\;"><strong>Date and Time:</strong> Saturdays\
 , April 4 &amp\; 11\, 2026\, 11 a.m.-3:30 p.m. PST\, Online</p><p style="
 line-height: 1.5\;"><strong>Instructor:</strong> Renee Fitzpatrick\, LMHC
 \, LPC\, CST</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;"><strong>Cost and Credits:</
 strong> $160\, includes 8 CEUs. Alumni\, Adjuncts\, and GSEC Clinical Sup
 ervisors save 20%. $75 GSEC student rate.&#160\;</p><p style="line-height
 : 1.5\;"><strong><a class="btn-small-style-1" href="https://lclark.tfafor
 ms.net/wf1W4MQ?epid=a1aUY0000026GiT" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Regis
 ter Online</a></strong></p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;"><em><strong>Regi
 stration ends after Wednesday\, April 1st</strong></em></p><div id="lw_wi
 dget_30f0017c" class="lw_widget lw_widget_type_blurbs lw_widget_blurbs lw
