SUMMARY:Lab Dog: Virtual Book Talk with Author\, Melanie Kaplan
DESCRIPTION:When journalist Melanie D.G. Kaplan adopted her beagle Hammy\
 , all she knew was that he had spent nearly four years in a research lab.
  Curious to know more about this gentle creature's past\, as well as the 
 broader world of animal research\, KaplanŌĆöwith Hammy in towŌĆöembarks o
 n a quest for answers. How did Hammy end up in a research facility? Why a
 re we still using millions of animals a year in experiments? What have we
  learned from them? Is there another way? In Lab Dog\, Kaplan investigate
 s the breeding and use of beagles for biomedical research\, drug and prod
 uct testing\, and education. Equal parts journalism and love story\, Lab 
 Dog offers a nuanced view on our relationship with a species that we both
  love and exploit\, and a reason to hope for a better future for all.  Th
 e event is online and open to the public. To register\, visit this link (
 https://lclark-edu.zoom.us/webinar/register/WN_xL5DHFBpQGuDHtfafH0kZw#/re
 gistration).  Lewis &amp\; Clark in-person students\, please join CALS to
  watch the virtual book talk in Wood Hall 7\, and a vegan lunch will be p
 rovided.Melanie is a longtime independent journalist whose travel and sci
 ence writing has appeared in The Atlantic\, the Washington Post\, the Wal
 l Street Journal\, and National Parks magazine. She is a graduate of Colu
 mbia Journalism School\, a 2021ŌĆō2022 MIT Knight Science Journalism fell
 ow\, and a third-generation Washington\, DC\, native.&#160\;
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  When journalist Melanie D.G. Kaplan ado
 pted her beagle Hammy\, all she knew was that he had spent nearly four ye
 ars in a research lab. Curious to know more about this gentle creature's 
 past\, as well as the broader world of animal research\, KaplanŌĆöwith Ha
 mmy in towŌĆöembarks on a quest for answers. How did Hammy end up in a re
 search facility? Why are we still using millions of animals a year in exp
 eriments? What have we learned from them? Is there another way? In <i>Lab
  Dog</i>\, Kaplan investigates the breeding and use of beagles for biomed
 ical research\, drug and product testing\, and education. Equal parts jou
 rnalism and love story\, <i>Lab Dog </i>offers a nuanced view on our rela
 tionship with a species that we both love and exploit\, and a reason to h
 ope for a better future for all.</p><p>  The event is online and open to 
 the public. To register\, <a href="https://lclark-edu.zoom.us/webinar/reg
 ister/WN_xL5DHFBpQGuDHtfafH0kZw#/registration">visit this link</a>.</p><p
 >  Lewis &amp\; Clark in-person students\, please join CALS to watch the 
 virtual book talk in Wood Hall 7\, and a vegan lunch will be provided.</p
 ><p><span class="il">Melanie</span> is a longtime independent journalist 
 whose travel and science writing has appeared in <i>The Atlantic</i>\, th
 e <i>Washington Post</i>\, the <i>Wall Street Journal</i>\, and <i>Nation
 al Parks</i> magazine. She is a graduate of Columbia Journalism School\, 
 a 2021ŌĆō2022 MIT Knight Science Journalism fellow\, and a third-generati
 on Washington\, DC\, native.&#160\;</p>
