SUMMARY:4 at 5 Lecture Series Featuring Pamplin Professor Emeritus Stephe
 n Dow Beckham ŌĆō Alaska Sojourners
DESCRIPTION:Alaska Sojourners: Remarkable Lives in the Last Frontier  In-
 person at L&amp\;CLindner Auditorium\, Miller Center for Humanities (Mill
 er 105)Livestream hosted by the L&amp\;C Alaska Alumni Chapter  Livestrea
 m link shared upon registration  Wednesday\, April 8\, 2026  5:00 - 6:00 
 P.M.Click to Register (https://engage.lclark.edu/register/?id=c195d64c-93
 d8-4b90-b942-106ba20ba031)Times for those joining remotely from other tim
 e zones:8 - 9 P.M. Eastern ŌŚÅ 7 - 8 P.M Central ŌŚÅ 6 - 7 P.M. Mountain 
  4 - 5 P.M. Alaska ŌŚÅ 2 - 3 P.M. Hawaii  This lecture series takes place
  the second Wednesday of every month\, February-May.About the lecture:  .
 Join this illuminating exploration of "Alaska Sojourners: Remarkable Live
 s in the Last Frontier." Through vivid biographical vignettes\, Professor
 . Beckham brings to life a cast of extraordinary Americans drawn to the A
 laska Territory following its purchase in 1867.  From naturalist John Mui
 r to the flamboyant "Klondike Kate" RockwellŌĆöwho spent her final days i
 n Sweet Home\, OregonŌĆöthese figures embody the spirit\, ambition\, and 
 artistry of a transformative era. Discover the stories of Alexander Panta
 ges\, the visionary theater impresario\; Rockwell Kent\, the artist and a
 uthor who found inspiration in Alaska's wild beauty\; Robert Service\, th
 e famed "Bard of the Yukon"\; and Jack London\, the rebellious writer who
 se adventures fueled his iconic fiction. The lecture also features Sydney
  Laurence\, a pioneering Alaskan painter\, and Nils P. Adamson\, a dedica
 ted lighthouse keeper near Skagway\, who\, along with his son\, tended th
 e harbor lights at Coos Bay for more than six decades.About the presenter
 :Stephen Dow Beckham is Pamplin Professor Emeritus of History at Lewis &a
 mp\; Clark College\, where he served for forty-two years. A preeminent au
 thority on the American West and the Lewis &amp\; Clark Expedition\, Prof
 essor Beckham dedicated the majority of his career to teaching undergradu
 ate students in the College of Arts and Sciences\, while also contributin
 g his expertise to the Law School's Indian Law Program.  Renowned for his
  immersive teaching\, he famously led field-based courses retracing the L
 ewis &amp\; Clark trail on horseback and sailing the Northwest Coast. Bey
 ond the classroom\, he has served as an expert witness in over forty trib
 al rights cases and currently chairs the Oregon Committee on Historic Pre
 servation. A former Oregon Professor of the Year and recipient of the Ame
 rican Historical Association's Asher Distinguished Teaching Award\, Profe
 ssor Beckham also serves on the board of the Theodore Roosevelt President
 ial Library\, continuing his lifelong commitment to historical scholarshi
 p and conservation.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p style="text-align: center\;"><strong>Alas
 ka Sojourners: Remarkable Lives in the Last Frontier<br /><br />  In-pers
 on at L&amp\;C<br /></strong>Lindner Auditorium\, Miller Center for Human
 ities (Miller 105)</p><p style="text-align: center\;"><strong>Livestream 
 hosted by the L&amp\;C Alaska Alumni Chapter</strong><br />  Livestream l
 ink shared upon registration<strong><br /></strong></p><p style="text-ali
 gn: center\;">  Wednesday\, April 8\, 2026<br />  5:00 - 6:00 P.M.</p><p 
 style="text-align: center\;"><strong><a class="btn-small-style-1 btn-smal
 l-style-1" href="https://engage.lclark.edu/register/?id=c195d64c-93d8-4b9
