 </strong></p><p style="text-align: center\;"><strong>Times for those join
 ing remotely from other time zones:<br /></strong>8 - 9 P.M. Eastern ŌŚÅ 
 7 - 8 P.M Central ŌŚÅ 6 - 7 P.M. Mountain<br />  4 - 5 P.M. Alaska ŌŚÅ 2 
 - 3 P.M. Hawaii</p><p style="text-align: left\;">  This lecture series ta
 kes place the second Wednesday of every month\, February-May.</p><p style
 ="text-align: left\;"><strong>About the lecture:</strong></p><p data-path
 -to-node="3">  .Join this illuminating exploration of <strong data-path-t
 o-node="3" data-index-in-node="80">"Alaska Sojourners: Remarkable Lives i
 n the Last Frontier."</strong> Through vivid biographical vignettes\, Pro
 fessor. Beckham brings to life a cast of extraordinary Americans drawn to
  the Alaska Territory following its purchase in 1867.</p><p data-path-to-
 node="4">  From naturalist John Muir to the flamboyant "Klondike Kate" Ro
 ckwellŌĆöwho spent her final days in Sweet Home\, OregonŌĆöthese figures 
 embody the spirit\, ambition\, and artistry of a transformative era. Disc
 over the stories of Alexander Pantages\, the visionary theater impresario
 \; Rockwell Kent\, the artist and author who found inspiration in Alaska'
 s wild beauty\; Robert Service\, the famed "Bard of the Yukon"\; and Jack
  London\, the rebellious writer whose adventures fueled his iconic fictio
 n. The lecture also features Sydney Laurence\, a pioneering Alaskan paint
 er\, and Nils P. Adamson\, a dedicated lighthouse keeper near Skagway\, w
 ho\, along with his son\, tended the harbor lights at Coos Bay for more t
 han six decades.</p><p><strong>About the presenter:</strong></p><p data-p
 ath-to-node="1"><strong data-path-to-node="1" data-index-in-node="0">Step
 hen Dow Beckham</strong> is Pamplin Professor Emeritus of History at Lewi
 s &amp\; Clark College\, where he served for forty-two years. A preeminen
 t authority on the American West and the Lewis &amp\; Clark Expedition\, 
 Professor Beckham dedicated the majority of his career to teaching underg
 raduate students in the College of Arts and Sciences\, while also contrib
 uting his expertise to the Law School's Indian Law Program.</p><p data-pa
 th-to-node="2">  Renowned for his immersive teaching\, he famously led fi
 eld-based courses retracing the Lewis &amp\; Clark trail on horseback and
  sailing the Northwest Coast. Beyond the classroom\, he has served as an 
 expert witness in over forty tribal rights cases and currently chairs the
  Oregon Committee on Historic Preservation. A former Oregon Professor of 
 the Year and recipient of the American Historical Association's Asher Dis
 tinguished Teaching Award\, Professor Beckham also serves on the board of
  the Theodore Roosevelt Presidential Library\, continuing his lifelong co
 mmitment to historical scholarship and conservation.</p>
