BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260417T090000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260417T160000
LOCATION:Lewis &amp\; Clark Graduate School
SUMMARY:Transforming Educator Development and Evaluation: A Growth-Orient
 ed Approach (In-Person)
DESCRIPTION:This workshop with Lori Cohen and Elizabeth Denevi\, PhD\, co
 -authors of Integrating Well-Being\, Growth\, and Evaluation: Four Founda
 tions for Leaders (https://www.routledge.com/Integrating-Educator-Well-Be
 ing-Growth-and-Evaluation-Four-Foundations-for-Leaders/Cohen-Denevi/p/boo
 k/9781032871813)\, will introduce a comprehensive and holistic framework 
 for transforming educator support systems using the metaphor of an ecosys
 tem.  School leaders will learn practical strategies for generating a vis
 ion for equity (Laying the Foundation)\, supporting collective and indivi
 dual well-being (Nurturing the Soil)\, identifying ways to support educat
 ors in their professional growth (Cultivating Continuous Learning)\, and 
 re-imagining evaluation for sustainable results (Tending the Ecosystem). 
  Through practical tools\, culturally-responsive and research-informed pr
 actices\, and case study examples\, participants will be able to generate
  actionable steps for addressing these foundationsŌĆöand develop a pathwa
 y for more cohesive and equitable educator support systems.  Participants
  in this workshop will:      Explore a framework that integrates equity\,
  well-being\, growth\, and evaluation\, and use this framework as a sprin
 gboard for determining areas of focus          Engage with practical tool
 s that promote reflection and systems change          Examine approaches 
 for redistributing power and resources to create genuine belonging    Col
 laborate with colleagues in multiple modalities          Reimagine growth
  and evaluation and develop an action and implementation plan to bring ba
 ck to their schools/organizations    Details &amp\; RegistrationDate and 
 Time: Friday\, April 17\, 2026\, 9 a.m.-4 p.m.Location: Lewis &amp\; Clar
 k Graduate School\, South Chapel\, Portland\, ORInstructors: Lori Cohen\,
  and Elizabeth Denevi\, PhDCost and Credits: $175\, includes 6 PDUs and a
  copy of the book\, Integrating Well-Being\, Growth\, and Evaluation: Fou
 r Foundations for Leaders (https://www.routledge.com/Integrating-Educator
 -Well-Being-Growth-and-Evaluation-Four-Foundations-for-Leaders/Cohen-Dene
 vi/p/book/9781032871813)Discounted Registration: GSEC Alumni and Adjuncts
  save 20%. GSEC Teacher Education\, Professional Administrator\, and Prin
 cipal License Mentors and Supervisors save 20%.Register Online (https://l
 clark.tfaforms.net/wf1W4MQ?epid=a1aUY000002IbUb)Registration closes after
  Tuesday\, April 14thAccessibility: We are committed to making our events
  accessible to all needs and abilities. When registering\, please let us 
 know your access needs. Contact us at 503-768-6040 or cce@lclark.edu (mai
 lto:cce@lclark.edu)&#160\;with questions.Please note: Discounted &#x2018\
 ;Student Rate&#x2019\; registrations are for current students only and do
  not include continuing education credit (CEU/PDUs)About the InstructorLo
 ri Cohen has three decades of experience in education\, serving as classr
 oom teacher\, coach\, building\, leader\, author\, and adjunct instructor
  at Lewis &amp\; Clark Graduate School of Education and Counseling. In he
 r capacity as an instructional coach\, teacher developer\, and building l
 eader\, she helped oversee the growth and evaluation models at her school
 . After many school-based roles\, she has worked with schools and distric
 ts around the world to reimagine systems of support\, taking an ecosystem
 s approach to transformational change.Elizabeth Denevi\, PhD\, is Assista
 nt Professor at Lewis &amp\; Clark Graduate School of Education and Couns
 eling with a focus on antiracist leadership. She also serves as the direc
 tor of Eastern Educational Resource Collaborative (East Ed)\, an educatio
 nal nonprofit that works with schools and colleges across the country to 
 promote equity and diversity pedagogy. She has served as both a PK-12 cla
 ssroom teacher and senior administrator. She is the co-author of Learning
  and Teaching While White: Antiracist Strategies for School Communities (
 2023) and Integrating Educator Well-being\, Growth\, and Evaluation: Four
  Foundations for Leaders (2025) both featured titles in Routledge's Equit
 y and Social Justice in Education series.New workshops and trainings are 
 added to our calendar regularly. For the latest on professional developme
 nt related to your specific interests\, sign up for our mailing list! (ht
 tps://lclark.tfaforms.net/4735441)
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  This worksho
 p with Lori Cohen and Elizabeth Denevi\, PhD\, co-authors of <i><a href="
 https://www.routledge.com/Integrating-Educator-Well-Being-Growth-and-Eval
 uation-Four-Foundations-for-Leaders/Cohen-Denevi/p/book/9781032871813" ta
 rget="_blank" rel="noopener">Integrating Well-Being\, Growth\, and Evalua
 tion: Four Foundations for Leaders</a></i><em>\,</em> will introduce a co
 mprehensive and holistic framework for transforming educator support syst
 ems using the metaphor of an ecosystem.</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">
   School leaders will learn practical strategies for generating a vision 
 for equity (<em>Laying the Foundation</em>)\, supporting collective and i
 ndividual well-being (<em>Nurturing the Soil</em>)\, identifying ways to 
 support educators in their professional growth (<em>Cultivating Continuou
 s Learning</em>)\, and re-imagining evaluation for sustainable results (<
 em>Tending the Ecosystem</em>).</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  Throug
 h practical tools\, culturally-responsive and research-informed practices
 \, and case study examples\, participants will be able to generate action
 able steps for addressing these foundationsŌĆöand develop a pathway for m
 ore cohesive and equitable educator support systems.</p><h4 class="p1">  
 Participants in this workshop will:</h4><ul><li class="p1"><p style="line
 -height: 1.5\;">      Explore a framework that <strong>integrates equity\
 , well-being\, growth\, and evaluation</strong>\, and use this framework 
 as a springboard for determining areas of focus    </p></li><li class="p1
 "><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">      Engage with <strong>practical tools
 </strong> that promote reflection and systems change    </p></li><li clas
 s="p1"><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">      Examine approaches for redistr
 ibuting power and resources to create genuine belonging    </p></li><li c
 lass="p1"><p style="line-height: 1.5\;"><strong>Collaborate with colleagu
 es</strong> in multiple modalities    </p></li><li class="p1"><p style="l
 ine-height: 1.5\;">      Reimagine growth and evaluation and <strong>deve
 lop an action and implementation plan</strong> to bring back to their sch
 ools/organizations    </p></li></ul><hr /><h3><strong>Details &amp\; Regi
 stration</strong></h3><p style="line-height: 1.5\;"><strong>Date and Time
 :</strong> Friday\, April 17\, 2026\, 9 a.m.-4 p.m.</p><p style="line-hei
 ght: 1.5\;"><strong>Location:</strong> Lewis &amp\; Clark Graduate School
 \, South Chapel\, Portland\, OR</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;"><strong>
 Instructors:</strong> Lori Cohen\, and Elizabeth Denevi\, PhD</p><p style
