SUMMARY:2026 Reception for Dorothy Berkson Writing Award in Gender Studies
DESCRIPTION:The 18th Annual Dorothy Berkson Writing Award in Gender Studi
 es presentation and reception will take place on Friday\, April 17\, 2026
  from 3 - 4:30 p.m. in Smith Hall.&#160\;  Refreshments will be served.  
 This award recognizes written achievement (e.g.\, scholarly essays\, rese
 arch projects\, creative non-fiction\, fiction\, poetry\, or playwriting)
  focused on gender and authored by a senior. The award winner will be hon
 ored at this reception that celebrates Professor Berkson's contributions 
 to Lewis &amp\; Clark College and the excellence of current students who 
 study gender through scholarly analysis and written expression.  Dorothy 
 Berkson\, professor emerita of English\, taught at Lewis &amp\; Clark Col
 lege from 1981 until her retirement in 2004. Professor Berkson was a pres
 enter in Lewis &amp\; Clark's first Gender Studies Symposium. For the gen
 der studies minor\, she designed a course titled Gender and Aesthetic Exp
 ression\, which she continued to teach for many years.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p><strong>The 18th Annual Dorothy Berkson W
 riting Award in Gender Studies presentation and reception will take place
  on Friday\, April 17\, 2026 from 3 - 4:30 p.m. in Smith Hall.&#160\;</st
 rong></p><p>  Refreshments will be served.</p><p>  This award recognizes 
 written achievement (e.g.\, scholarly essays\, research projects\, creati
 ve non-fiction\, fiction\, poetry\, or playwriting) focused on gender and
  authored by a senior. The award winner will be honored at this reception
  that celebrates Professor Berkson's contributions to Lewis &amp\; Clark 
 College and the excellence of current students who study gender through s
 cholarly analysis and written expression.</p><p>  Dorothy Berkson\, profe
 ssor emerita of English\, taught at Lewis &amp\; Clark College from 1981 
 until her retirement in 2004. Professor Berkson was a presenter in Lewis 
 &amp\; Clark's first Gender Studies Symposium. For the gender studies min
 or\, she designed a course titled Gender and Aesthetic Expression\, which
  she continued to teach for many years.</p>
