BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260424T090000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260424T140000
LOCATION:Online
SUMMARY:Identifying and Understanding Autism in Women: Assessment Through
  Intervention (Online)
DESCRIPTION:This presentation for mental health practitioners aims to dee
 pen understanding of how autism and related forms of neurodivergence pres
 ent in girls and women\, and to support more accurate\, ethical\, and aff
 irming identification and care.  Autism is a complex and multifaceted for
 m of neurodivergence\, encompassing a wide range of traits that can prese
 nt differently across individuals\, contexts\, and developmental stages. 
 The most widely-recognized presentation of autism is generally based on r
 esearch conducted on white\, middle- to upper-class males\, often emphasi
 zing conventionally "masculine" interests and behaviors.  As a result\, m
 uch of the diagnostic criteria for autism and ADHD in the DSM does not&#1
 60\;capture how neurodivergence presents in girls\, women\, transgender a
 nd nonbinary individuals\, and people of color.Many autistic females and 
 gender-diverse individuals are misdiagnosed\, overlooked\, or misundersto
 od in childhood\, with their traits minimized\, masked\, or misinterprete
 d as behavioral or emotional difficulties rather than recognized as neuro
 developmental differences.  Recent research finds that nearly 80% of auti
 stic females are undiagnosed as of the age of 18.  This presentation will
  explore the following:Neurodivergence in girls and women: How traits in 
 females both align with and diverge from DSM criteria\, including differe
 nces in cognitive and sensory processing\, executive functioning\, social
  cognition\, communication\, and the influence of gendered expectations o
 n identification    Masking and it's impact: What is it\, how does it dev
 elop\, and its long- and short- term consequences    Assessment and refer
 ral: Best practices\, including timing\, developmentally sensitive testin
 g\, ethical and equity-informed considerations\, and neurodiversity-affir
 ming language\, and Theory of Mind&#160\;    Treatment and Support: Nervo
 us systemŌĆōinformed\, strengths-based interventions that support unmaski
 ng and self-understanding\, prevent autistic burnout\, and promote sustai
 nable functioning through individualized\, neurodiversity-affirming treat
 ment plans      This workshop may meet the OBLPCT Cultural Competence Con
 tinuing Education requirement. Click here for more information (http://ww
 w.oregon.gov/oblpct/Pages/CCCE.aspx)Details &amp\; RegistrationDate and T
 ime: Friday\, April 24\, 2026\, 9 a.m.-2 p.m.Presenter: Ashley Taylor\, P
 syDCost and Credits: $105\, includes 4 CEUs. $45 student rate. GSEC Alumn
 i and Adjuncts save 20%  No-cost registration available for GSEC Mental H
 ealth Clinical Supervisors\, Faculty\, and Staff. Email cce@lclark.edu (m
 ailto:cce@lclark.ed) with your request to register.Register Online (https
 ://lclark.tfaforms.net/wf1W4MQ?epid=a1aUY000002Iqwf)Accessibility: We are
  committed to making our events accessible to all needs and abilities. Wh
 en registering\, please let us know your access needs. Contact us at 503-
 768-6040 or cce@lclark.edu (mailto:cce@lclark.edu)&#160\;with questions.P
 lease note: Discounted &#x2018\;Student Rate&#x2019\; registrations are f
 or current students only and do not include continuing education credit (
 CEU/PDUs)About the PresentersDr. Ashley Taylor is a licensed clinical psy
 chologist in California and Washington State\, author\, and founder of Wo
 nder Tree Developmental Psychology. She specializes in providing comprehe
 nsive evaluations through a reflective\, neurodiversity affirming lens. S
 he has provided high quality care to those with neurodivergence for over 
 15 years. Dr. Taylor lives in Southwest Washington with her husband and t
 wo boys. She has recently become a yoga teacher and enjoys spending time 
 with her family\, pets\, going hiking\, snowboarding\, and doing yoga. Wo
 nder Tree Developmental Psychology has locations in Vancouver\, Washingto
 n and Pasadena\, California\, providing an excellent team of developmenta
 l psychologists\, occupational therapists\, and educational specialists t
 hat support developmental across the lifespan.New workshops and trainings
  are added to our calendar regularly. For the latest on professional deve
 lopment related to your specific interests\, sign up for our mailing list
 ! (https://lclark.tfaforms.net/4735441)
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  This present
 ation for mental health practitioners aims to deepen understanding of how
  autism and related forms of neurodivergence present in girls and women\,
  and to support more accurate\, ethical\, and affirming identification an
 d care.</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  Autism is a complex and multif
 aceted form of neurodivergence\, encompassing a wide range of traits that
  can present differently across individuals\, contexts\, and developmenta
 l stages. The most widely-recognized presentation of autism is generally 
 based on research conducted on white\, middle- to upper-class males\, oft
 en emphasizing conventionally "masculine" interests and behaviors.</p><p 
 style="line-height: 1.5\;">  As a result\, much of the diagnostic criteri
 a for autism and ADHD in the DSM does not&#160\;capture how neurodivergen
 ce presents in girls\, women\, transgender and nonbinary individuals\, an
 d people of color.</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;"><span style="backgrou
 nd-color: transparent\;">Many autistic females and gender-diverse individ
 uals are misdiagnosed\, overlooked\, or misunderstood in childhood\, with
  their traits minimized\, masked\, or misinterpreted as behavioral or emo
 tional difficulties rather than recognized as neurodevelopmental differen
 ces.</span></p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  Recent research finds that
  nearly 80% of autistic females are undiagnosed as of the age of 18.</p><
 h4>  This presentation will explore the following:</h4><ul><li><p style="
 line-height: 1.5\;"><strong>Neurodivergence in girls and women:</strong> 
 How traits in females both align with and diverge from DSM criteria\, inc
 luding differences in cognitive and sensory processing\, executive functi
 oning\, social cognition\, communication\, and the influence of gendered 
 expectations on identification    </p></li><li><p style="line-height: 1.5
 \;"><strong>Masking and it's impact:</strong> What is it\, how does it de
 velop\, and its long- and short- term consequences    </p></li><li><p sty
 le="line-height: 1.5\;"><strong>Assessment and referral:</strong> Best pr
 actices\, including timing\, developmentally sensitive testing\, ethical 
 and equity-informed considerations\, and neurodiversity-affirming languag
 e\, and Theory of Mind&#160\;    </p></li><li><p style="line-height: 1.5\
 ;"><strong>Treatment and Support:</strong> Nervous systemŌĆōinformed\, st
 rengths-based interventions that support unmasking and self-understanding
 \, prevent autistic burnout\, and promote sustainable functioning through
  individualized\, neurodiversity-affirming treatment plans    </p></li></
 ul><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  This workshop may meet the OBLPCT Cult
 ural Competence Continuing Education requirement. <a href="http://www.ore
 gon.gov/oblpct/Pages/CCCE.aspx">Click here for more information</a></p><h
 r /><h2><strong>Details &amp\; Registration</strong></h2><p style="line-h
 eight: 1.5\;"><strong>Date and Time:</strong> Friday\, April 24\, 2026\, 
 9 a.m.-2 p.m.</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;"><strong>Presenter:</strong
 > Ashley Taylor\, PsyD</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;"><strong>Cost and 
 Credits:</strong> $105\, includes 4 CEUs. $45 student rate. GSEC Alumni a
 nd Adjuncts save 20%</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  No-cost registrat
 ion available for GSEC Mental Health Clinical Supervisors\, Faculty\, and
  Staff. Email <a href="mailto:cce@lclark.ed">cce@lclark.edu</a> with your
  request to register.</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;"><strong><a class="
 btn-small-style-1" href="https://lclark.tfaforms.net/wf1W4MQ?epid=a1aUY00
 0002Iqwf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Register Online</a></strong></p>
