DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260425T090000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260425T100000
LOCATION:Lewis &amp\; Clark Graduate School\, TBA
SUMMARY:Ethical Considerations in Psychedelic-Assisted Psychotherapy (In-
 Person)
DESCRIPTION:This course offers an overview of the integration aspect of p
 sychedelic-assisted therapy\, and examines ethical considerations that ca
 n impact the overall and long-term experience of clients receiving treatm
 ent.  We will focus on integration as an intentional process of bringing 
 awareness to the impact of the psychedelic experience and applying it to 
 one's life in ways that can be transformative.  Ethical issues\, harm red
 uction interventions in psychedelic-assisted therapy practices\, and anth
 ropocentric and biocentric perspectives on working with psychedelic medic
 ines in therapy will be discussed.Following the completion of this course
 \, participants should have a better understanding of:How to apply tools 
 to conceptualize and facilitate integration practices.  Affirmative ethic
 s and harm reduction frameworks\, and how they apply to psychedelic-assis
 ted psychotherapy.  Psychedelic-assisted psychotherapy from a biocentric 
 perspective\, which focuses on the relationship between humans\, plant me
 dicines\, psychedelic medicines\, and psychotherapy.  Integrating the div
 ersity\, equity\, and inclusion dimensions of everyday life and clinical 
 work into psychedelic therapy.  Course Details &amp\; RegistrationDates a
 nd Times: Saturday-Sunday\, April 25-26\, 2026\, 9 a.m.-5:30 p.m.Location
 : Lewis &amp\; Clark Graduate School\, Portland\, OregonInstructors: Eliz
 abeth Hoke\, LMFT\; and Veronica Vargas\, LPCGraduate-level Continuing Ed
 ucation credit: CECP-866-01\, 1 semester hour\, $375Register Online (http
 s://lclark.tfaforms.net/4735371)  &#160\;We are committed to making our e
 vents accessible to all needs and abilities. If you have a disability tha
 t may impact your academic performance\, you may request accommodations b
 y meeting with the Office of Student Accessibility staff and submitting d
 ocumentation on the Office of Student Accessibility website (/offices/stu
 dent-accessibility/). Please be aware that the process for evaluation and
  implementation of accommodations could take 2-3 weeks\, so please be in 
 touch with the OSA as soon as possible. Email access@lclark.edu (mailto:a
 ccess@lclark.edu) with any additional questions or concerns.About the Ins
 tructors Elizabeth Hoke\, MFT is the Clinical Director of Liberation Inst
 itute in Portland where she supervises and provides psychoeducational tra
 inings and workshops. She specializes in working with addiction recovery 
 and ADHD\, using a mix of theoretical tools rooted in somatic psychology 
 and biocentric philosophies. Elizabeth co-facilitates ketamine-assisted p
 sychotherapy sessions at Rainfall Medicine and co-leads addiction recover
 y support groups at Portland Psychedelic Society and the Rhizome. She has
  completed the 100-hour MDMA Therapy Training program through the Multidi
 sciplinary Association for Psychedelic Studies. Elizabeth also co-created
  the Entheogen Assisted Psychotherapy and Integration Training Series for
  licensed professionals at Lewis &amp\; Clark Graduate School Center for 
 Community Engagement in 2021. Veronica Vargas\, MA\, LPC journeys alongsi
 de folks in their path towards healing\, harmony\, and contentment. She f
 inds beauty in witnessing the unfolding of human potential\, and cultivat
 ion of meaning. Her formal training is in counseling psychology with an e
 mphasis in depth-psychotherapy. Depth-psychotherapy can be defined as a h
 olistic approach that examines all aspects of a person's life\, including
  dreams\, art\, fantasies\, philosophies\, and conscious thoughts. She wa
 s heavily influenced by the work of Swiss psychiatrist\, Carl Gustav Jung
 . In her work as a licensed psychotherapist she assesses the whole person
  or family system by looking at relational and cultural systems\; spiritu
 ality\; personal and intergenerational trauma\; systems of oppression\; p
 ersonal values and how they are or aren't reflected authentically in the 
 person's life. She has a private practice in Portland\, Oregon where she 
 offers psychotherapy\, dream work\, and psychedelic integration therapy. 
 .  &#160\;New workshops and trainings are added to our calendar regularly
 . For the latest on professional development related to your specific int
 erests\, sign up for our mailing list! (https://lclark.tfaforms.net/47354
 41)
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p style="line-height: 1.6\;">  This course 
 offers an overview of the integration aspect of psychedelic-assisted ther
 apy\, and examines ethical considerations that can impact the overall and
  long-term experience of clients receiving treatment.</p><p style="line-h
 eight: 1.6\;">  We will focus on integration as an intentional process of
  bringing awareness to the impact of the psychedelic experience and apply
 ing it to one's life in ways that can be transformative.</p><p style="lin
 e-height: 1.6\;">  Ethical issues\, harm reduction interventions in psych
 edelic-assisted therapy practices\, and anthropocentric and biocentric pe
 rspectives on working with psychedelic medicines in therapy will be discu
 ssed.</p><p style="line-height: 1.6\;"><strong>Following the completion o
 f this course\, participants should have a better understanding of:</stro
 ng></p><ul><li style="line-height: 1.6\;">How to apply tools to conceptua
 lize and facilitate integration practices.  </li><li style="line-height: 
 1.6\;">Affirmative ethics and harm reduction frameworks\, and how they ap
 ply to psychedelic-assisted psychotherapy.  </li><li style="line-height: 
