LOCATION:Online
SUMMARY:Fat Studies & Health at Every Size (Online)
DESCRIPTION:This course explores the interdisciplinary field of scholarsh
 ip in Fat Studies that aims to debunk weight-centric misconceptions and c
 ountering mainstream narratives.  Participants will examine fat bias\, fa
 t shame and weight-based oppression as a social justice issue that inters
 ects with other systems of oppression.  This course includes an introduct
 ion to the paradigm of Health At Every Size (HAES)\, a weight-neutral app
 roach to health promotion that emphasizes size diversity\, intuitive eati
 ng\, and joyful movement. HAES is also an important paradigm in working w
 ith people who experience disordered eating.  This course is part of our 
 Eating Disorders Certificate Program (https://graduate.lclark.edu/program
 s/continuing_education/certificates/eating_disorders/).&#160\;Course Deta
 ils &amp\; RegistrationDates &amp\; Times: Saturday-Sunday\, April 25-26\
 , 2026\, 9 a.m.-5:30 p.m.Instructor: Krystal Marcinkiewicz\, MA\, LPC\, L
 MHCCurrent Students and Certificate Candidates: CECP 835-02\, 1 semester 
 hour of Graduate Continuing Education Credit\, $375. Contact ccecerts@lcl
 ark.edu (mailto:ccecerts@lclark.edu) with questions.Register Online (http
 s://lclark.tfaforms.net/4735425)Individual Class: We welcome students see
 king to take individual courses within the certificate program. Admission
  to the program is required. Click here for more information (https://www
 .lclark.edu/programs/continuing_education/certificates/eating_disorders/#
 Admission)We are committed to making our events accessible to all needs a
 nd abilities. If you have a disability that may impact your academic perf
 ormance\, you may request accommodations by meeting with the Office of St
 udent Accessibility staff and submitting documentation on the Office of S
 tudent Accessibility website (/offices/student-accessibility/). Please be
  aware that the process for evaluation and implementation of accommodatio
 ns could take 2-3 weeks\, so please be in touch with the OSA as soon as p
 ossible. Email access@lclark.edu (mailto:access@lclark.edu) with any addi
 tional questions or concerns.About the InstructorKrystal Marcinkiewicz\, 
 MA\, LPC\, LMHC is a Licensed Professional Counselor and Clinical Supervi
 sor\, having earned her Masters Degree in Professional Mental Health Coun
 seling from Lewis &amp\; Clark College in 2018. Drawing from an integrati
 ve feminist approach\, her work is grounded in person-centered values\, e
 mphasizing authentic connection\, and collaborative engagement. Her prima
 ry clinical focus is supporting clients in navigating identity developmen
 t\, body politics\, neurodivergence\, emotional codependency\, highly sen
 sitive personalities and other complex emotional experiences.  In additio
 n to clinical work\, Krystal is also passionate in training and mentoring
  emerging counselors. She is an adjunct professor\, teaching a wide varie
 ty of graduate counseling courses with an underlying emphasis on counselo
 r identity development\, reflective practice\, and cultivating profession
 al resilience.  In both the classroom\, and her clinical work\, Krystal i
 s committed to creating affirming spaces that honor intersectional identi
 ties and lived experience.New workshops and trainings are added to our ca
 lendar regularly. For the latest on professional development related to y
 our specific interests\, sign up for our mailing list! (https://lclark.tf
 aforms.net/4735441)
