BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260513T170000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260513T190000
LOCATION:Miller Hall\, Room 105 (Lindner Auditorium)
GEO:45.450858;-122.668265
SUMMARY:4 at 5 Lecture Series Featuring Pamplin Professor Emeritus Stephe
 n Dow Beckham ŌĆō The Pig War and Series Closing Reception
DESCRIPTION:The Pig War: The San Juan Islands in ConflictFollowed by Lect
 ure Series Closing Reception  In-person at L&amp\;CLindner Auditorium\, M
 iller Center for Humanities (Miller 105)Livestream hosted by the L&amp\;C
  Washington Alumni Chapter  Livestream link shared upon registration  Wed
 nesday\, May 13\, 2026  5:00 - 7:00 P.M. (in-person)  5:00 - 6:00 P.M. (o
 nline)Click to Register (https://engage.lclark.edu/register/?id=c195d64c-
 93d8-4b90-b942-106ba20ba031)Times for those joining remotely from other t
 ime zones:8 - 9 P.M. Eastern ŌŚÅ 7 - 8 P.M Central ŌŚÅ 6 - 7 P.M. Mountai
 n  4 - 5 P.M. Alaska ŌŚÅ 2 - 3 P.M. Hawaii  This lecture series takes pla
 ce the second Wednesday of every month\, February-May.About the Lecture  
 Professor Beckham presents "The Pig War: San Juan Islands in Conflict\, 1
 859ŌĆō1872\," a lecture detailing the international controversy in Puget 
 Sound that nearly brought the United States and Great Britain to war. Thi
 s historical event resonates with modern tensions regarding the 49th para
 llel boundary\, tariffs\, and sovereign rights.  Prof. Beckham examines h
 ow the killing of a pig on San Juan Island precipitated an outrageous exp
 losion of conflict over the exact location of the boundary between Canada
  and the United States. The "Pig War" led to a significant build-up of ar
 my and navy forces and the construction of fortifications\, with tensions
  only ultimately resolved through international arbitration by Kaiser Wil
 helm I of Germany.  Using historical photographs\, watercolors\, and maps
 \, Prof. Beckham places the San Juan Islands conflict within the broader 
 context of the American Civil War\, boundary disputes in the Stikine Rive
 r watershed\, fisheries off the coast of Nova Scotia\, and American claim
 s against England regarding the sinking of Union vessels by the British-b
 uilt\, Confederate-operated CSS Alabama.About the PresenterStephen Dow Be
 ckham is Pamplin Professor Emeritus of History at Lewis &amp\; Clark Coll
 ege\, where he served for forty-two years. A preeminent authority on the 
 American West and the Lewis &amp\; Clark Expedition\, Professor Beckham d
 edicated the majority of his career to teaching undergraduate students in
  the College of Arts and Sciences\, while also contributing his expertise
  to the Law School's Indian Law Program.  Renowned for his immersive teac
 hing\, he famously led field-based courses retracing the Lewis &amp\; Cla
 rk trail on horseback and sailing the Northwest Coast. Beyond the classro
 om\, he has served as an expert witness in over forty tribal rights cases
  and currently chairs the Oregon Committee on Historic Preservation. A fo
 rmer Oregon Professor of the Year and recipient of the American Historica
 l Association's Asher Distinguished Teaching Award\, Professor Beckham al
 so serves on the board of the Theodore Roosevelt Presidential Library\, c
 ontinuing his lifelong commitment to historical scholarship and conservat
 ion.  &#160\;
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p style="text-align: center\;"><strong>The 
 Pig War: The San Juan Islands in Conflict</strong></p><p style="text-alig
 n: center\;"><strong>Followed by Lecture Series Closing Reception<br /><b
 r />  In-person at L&amp\;C<br /></strong>Lindner Auditorium\, Miller Cen
 ter for Humanities (Miller 105)</p><p style="text-align: center\;"><stron
 g>Livestream hosted by the L&amp\;C Washington Alumni Chapter</strong><br
  />  Livestream link shared upon registration<strong><br /></strong></p><
 p style="text-align: center\;">  Wednesday\, May 13\, 2026<br />  5:00 - 
 7:00 P.M. (in-person)<br />  5:00 - 6:00 P.M. (online)</p><p style="text-
 align: center\;"><strong><a class="btn-small-style-1 btn-small-style-1" h
 ref="https://engage.lclark.edu/register/?id=c195d64c-93d8-4b90-b942-106ba
 20ba031" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Click to Register</a></strong></p
 ><p style="text-align: center\;"><strong>Times for those joining remotely
  from other time zones:<br /></strong>8 - 9 P.M. Eastern ŌŚÅ 7 - 8 P.M Ce
 ntral ŌŚÅ 6 - 7 P.M. Mountain<br />  4 - 5 P.M. Alaska ŌŚÅ 2 - 3 P.M. Haw
 aii</p><p style="text-align: left\;">  This lecture series takes place th
 e second Wednesday of every month\, February-May.</p><p><strong>About the
  Lecture</strong></p><p data-path-to-node="3">  Professor Beckham present
 s <strong data-path-to-node="3" data-index-in-node="35">"The Pig War: San
  Juan Islands in Conflict\, 1859ŌĆō1872\,"</strong> a lecture detailing t
 he international controversy in Puget Sound that nearly brought the Unite
 d States and Great Britain to war. This historical event resonates with m
 odern tensions regarding the 49th parallel boundary\, tariffs\, and sover
 eign rights.</p><p data-path-to-node="4">  Prof. Beckham examines how the
  killing of a pig on San Juan Island precipitated an outrageous explosion
  of conflict over the exact location of the boundary between Canada and t
 he United States. The "Pig War" led to a significant build-up of army and
  navy forces and the construction of fortifications\, with tensions only 
 ultimately resolved through international arbitration by Kaiser Wilhelm I
  of Germany.</p><p data-path-to-node="5">  Using historical photographs\,
  watercolors\, and maps\, Prof. Beckham places the San Juan Islands confl
 ict within the broader context of the American Civil War\, boundary dispu
 tes in the <strong data-path-to-node="5" data-index-in-node="183">Stikine
  River</strong> watershed\, fisheries off the coast of Nova Scotia\, and 
 American claims against England regarding the sinking of Union vessels by
  the British-built\, Confederate-operated <strong data-path-to-node="5" d
 ata-index-in-node="366">CSS Alabama</strong>.</p><p><strong>About the Pre
 senter</strong></p><p data-path-to-node="1"><strong data-path-to-node="1"
  data-index-in-node="0">Stephen Dow Beckham</strong> is Pamplin Professor
  Emeritus of History at Lewis &amp\; Clark College\, where he served for 
 forty-two years. A preeminent authority on the American West and the Lewi
 s &amp\; Clark Expedition\, Professor Beckham dedicated the majority of h
 is career to teaching undergraduate students in the College of Arts and S
 ciences\, while also contributing his expertise to the Law School's India
 n Law Program.</p><p data-path-to-node="2">  Renowned for his immersive t
 eaching\, he famously led field-based courses retracing the Lewis &amp\; 
 Clark trail on horseback and sailing the Northwest Coast. Beyond the clas
 sroom\, he has served as an expert witness in over forty tribal rights ca
 ses and currently chairs the Oregon Committee on Historic Preservation. A
  former Oregon Professor of the Year and recipient of the American Histor
 ical Association's Asher Distinguished Teaching Award\, Professor Beckham
  also serves on the board of the Theodore Roosevelt Presidential Library\
 , continuing his lifelong commitment to historical scholarship and conser
 vation.</p><p style="text-align: center\;">  &#160\;</p>
